sec.p:
Osteoporosis is a systemic bone disease characterised by reduced bone mass, impaired bone quality, and decreased bone strength, which causes bone fragility and fracture (

). Osteoporosis is a common disease among older women (

); indeed, one third of women over the age of 50 will suffer from osteoporosis (

). owing to its insidious onset, symptoms of osteoporosis do not manifest until the fracture occurs, thus posing a serious threat to women’ s health (

). Osteoporosis is associated with decreased estrogen levels in postmenopausal women (

). Estrogen plays important roles in bone resorption and formation in many ways (

). It activates the Wnt/β- catenin signalling pathway, which promotes the differentiation and maturation of bone marrow mesenchymal stem cells (BMSCs) into osteoblasts (

; 

). Moreover, estrogen inhibits the levels of osteoclast differentiation factors IL-1, IL-6, IL-7, and TNF-α, and induces osteoclast apoptosis through the Fasl pathway (

). And estrogen affects differentiation by regulating the ratio of RANKL/OPG (

). Therefore, estrogen replacement therapy (ERT) is the preferred treatment for early menopause. ERT supplements help relieve menopause-associated symptoms, but simultaneously bring some adverse effects, such as the increasing risk of breast cancer and stroke (

). For this reason, researchers are committed to seeking estrogen substitutes, among which phytoestrogen (PE), a mild estrogen analogue, has become a research hotspot (

).

The mature fruit of 

Psoralea corylifolia

L. (Leguminosae) is a common traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) used to tonify the kidney and yang, and to treat colitis, pollakiuria, osteoporosis, eczema and leucoderma (

). It is also used as a natural food additive (

). Kidney-tonifying TCM is used for the treatment of osteoporosis, based on the TCM theory that bone growth depends on the nourishment of kidney essence (

). PE from fruits of 

P. corylifolia

. is the material basis for anti-osteoporosis. For example, psoralidin promotes osteogenesis and inhibits the adipogenesis of BMSCs, while suppressing bone loss in ovariectomised rats (

; 

). Meanwhile neobavaisoflavone inhibits osteoclastogenesis, promotes osteogenesis, and ameliorates bone loss in ovariectomised mice (

).

With the aim of identifying the anti-osteoporosis constituents of 

P. corylifolia

, a systematic phytochemical study was carried out. Plant material (
47.9 kg
) was extracted with 70% ethanol. The crude extract was partitioned successively with cyclohexane (cHe), ethyl acetate (EtOAc), and normal butanol (
n
-BuOH). The EtOAc extract was separated using various column chromatography methods. Fortunately, diverse structures were obtained. In our previous study, four flavonones and chalcones (

), 17 heterodimers of meroterpene phenol (

), and 22 meroterpene phenols (

) were identified. In this study, we report a further109 compounds (
1–109
) (
Fig. S1
), containing 37 undescribed compounds (1–6, 18–33, 53–60, 74–75, 94, 103–105, 106) (
Fig. 1
). The identified compounds included 17 coumarins (
1–17
), 35 isoflavones (18–52), 21 flavonones (53–73), 20 chalcones (74–93), 6 flavones (94–99), 3 benzofurans (
100–102
), 3 chromones (
103–105
), 2 isoflavanols (106 and 107), and 2 glycosides (108 and 109). Herein, the structures of undescribed compounds were elucidated and the structures of some coumarins (
7–10
) were corrected.

Bavacoumestan G ( 2 ), a white amorphous powder, possessed the molecular formula C 22 H 20 O 7 . Its 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra (Tables S1 and S2) showed similar signals and splitting patterns to those of bavacoumestan C (
) and epi -bavacoumestan C (
). However, signals of the ethyl group at δ H 3.73 and δ H 1.17 were observed, and it was combined to C-3 ′′ by key HMBC correlations from H–OCH 2 CH 3 at δ H 3.73 to C-3 ′′ at δ C 77.9 ( Fig. 2 ). The key HMBC correlation from H-8 at δ H 7.12 to C-10 at δ C 105.5 indicated that the isopentenyl group was located at C-6. Accordingly, the structure of compound 2 was established. The relative configurations of C-2 ′′ and C-3 ′′ were constructed as trans by the small coupling constant ( J ′′ 2,3 ′′ = 2.8 Hz) (
;
). Interestingly, the NMR data of compounds 8 and 9 were the same as those of bavacoumestan C and epi -bavacoumestan C, respectively (Table S13). However, further HMBC analysis showed cross-peaks of H-8 ( δ H 7.06 for 8, δ H 7.06 for 9) and C-10 ( δ C 105.6 for 8, δ C 105.8 for 9), indicating that their isopentenyl groups were combined on C-6 instead of C-5’. We found that the chemical shifts at C-10 and C-1 ′ were mistakenly assigned to bavacoumestan C and epi -bavacoumestan C (
;
). In fact, the chemical shifts of C-10 were 105.3 and 106.1 ppm, and the chemical shifts of C-1 ′ were δ C 114.5 and 115.0 ppm. This indicated that the isopentenyl groups were located at C- 6 in bavacoumestan C and epi -bavacoumestan C ( Fig. 1 ). In the same manner, we redefined the structures of compounds 7 (bavacoumestan B) and 10 using HMBC experiments. We first reported the 13 C NMR data of 10 and named it bavacoumestan L. Fortunately, we could successfully cultivate crystals of 7 and 8, and their crystal structures ( Fig. 3 ) were undoubtedly consistent with the above-mentioned analysis. Ultimately, the absolute configuration of 2 was confirmed as 2 ′′ S ,3 ′′ S based on its biosynthesis relationship with bavacoumestan B ( 7 ).

Bavaisoflavone E ( 22 ) was assigned the molecular formula C 20 H 18 O 6 , indicating 12 degrees of unsaturation. With NMR data (Tables S3 and S4), the compound was identified as a prenylated isoflavone with dihydrofuran, and it had a planar structure similar to that of corylifol E ( 34 ) (
). However, the coupling constant ( J ′′ 2,3 ′′ =6.1 Hz) of compound 22 was different from that ( J ′′ 2,3" =3.7 Hz) of corylifol E ( 34 ), indicating a cis configuration of the two protons (
;
). The chiral centre of compound 35 (Corylifol D) at the C-2 ′′ position was deduced to be R by the negative optical value ([ α ]25 D 16.00) (
). Therefore, the absolute configuration of 22 was established as 2 ′′ R ,3 ′′ S based on their biogenetic synthesis relationships.

Bavaisoflavone G ( 24 ) was assigned the molecular formula C 20 H 18 O 5 based on the HR-ESI-MS ion at m/z 339.1230 [M + H] + (calcd for 339.1232). Its NMR data (Tables S3 and S4) were similar to those of daidzein ( 44 ) (
) except for an isopentenyl group at C-8, by HMBC cross-peaks between H-3 ′′ at δ H 3.32 and C-7 at δ C 165.0. However, isopentenyl was cyclised to form a dihydrofuran ring by 1 H NMR signals at δ H 4.83 (1H, t, J =8.9 Hz, H-2 ′′ ) and 3.32 (2H, d, J =8.9 Hz, H-3 ′′ ), and 13 C NMR signals at δ C 91.6 for C-2 ′′ and 27.0 for C-3 ′′ . Thus, the planar structure of 24 was constructed. The absolute configuration assigned at C-2 ′′ was R by the negative optical value ([ α ]25 D 16.00) (
).

Bavaisoflavone I ( 26 ) was assigned the molecular formula C 25 H 28 O 6 by the HR-ESI-MS ion at m/z 423.1808 [M – H] (calcd for 423.1808), revealing that the compound was a variant of corylifol A ( 49 ) (
). In the NMR spectra (Tables S5 and S6), signals of the fragment between C-1 ′′ and C-5 ′′ highly overlapped with those of corylifol A ( 49 ), indicating their same structural units. However, the HMBC correlations ( Fig. 2 ) from CH 3 -8 ′′ at δ H 1.09 to C-6 ′′ at δ C 79.1 and C-7 ′′ at δ C 74.1 determined a 6 ′′ , 7 ′′ -dihydroxyl fragment, which replaced one group of double-bond signals between C-6 ′′ and C-7 ′′ . The absolute configuration of 6 ′′ S was assigned by a positive Cotton effect at 305 nm (
) in Rh 2 (OCOCF 3 ) 4 -ICD spectrum (Fig. S7). Therefore, the structure of compound 26 was established successfully ( Fig. 1 ).

Bavaisoflavone M ( 30 ) was obtained as yellowish amorphous powders, and its molecular formula was determined to be C 25 H 26 O 6 based on HR-ESI-MS ion at m/z 423.1805 [M +H] + (calcd for 423.1808). Similar 1 H and 13 C NMR signals (Tables S5 and S6) between 30 and 29 were observed with the exception of the carbon chemical shift at C-2 ′′ ( δ C 96.3 for 30; δ C 80.2 for 29). The downfield chemical shift at C-2 ′′ indicated that the geranyl moiety in corylifol A ( 49 ) was cyclised to form a dihydrofuran ring. The small coupling constant ( J ′′ 2,3 ′′ = 4.8 Hz) determined that the relative configurations of C-2 ′′ and C-3 ′′ were trans (
;
). The NOE correlations between H-2 ′′ at δ H 4.23 and CH 3 -11 ′′ at δ H 1.13 indicated the relative position of the methyl group ( Fig. S2 ). Accordingly, the structure of 30 was constructed ( Fig. 1 ).

Bavaisoflavone N ( 31 ) and bavaisoflavone O ( 32 ) shared the same molecular formulas as C 25 H 24 O 5 . Their NMR data (Tables S5 and S6) were highly similar to those of neocorylin ( 37 ) (
), with the exception of the terminal isopentenyl group. The HMBC correlations from CH 3 -9 ′′ /10 ′′ at δ H 1.21 to C-8 ′′ at δ C 71.5 suggested the presence of a hydroxyl group on C-8 ′′ in compound 31 ( Fig. 2 ). The presence of a double bond at C-6 ′′ and C-7 ′′ was supported by their carbon chemical shifts at δ C 122.4 and 143.4, and the key HMBC correlation from H-6 ′′ at δ H 5.66 to C-8 ′′ . Therefore, the structure of 31 was established in Fig. 1 . However, one terminal double bond replaced a methyl group at C-9 ′′ in compound 32, via key HMBC correlations from H-9 ′′ at δ H 4.90 and 4.80 to C-10 ′′ at δ C 17.9. A hydroxyl replacement at C-7 ′′ occurred via HMBC cross-peaks from H-9 ′′ to C-7 ′′ at δ C 77.0. The absolute configuration of C-7 ′′ was assigned as S based on the positive Cotton effect at 300 nm (
) in the Rh 2 (OCOCF 3 ) 4 -ICD spectrum (Fig. S7). Accordingly, the structure of 32 was constructed.

Bavachinone E ( 55 ), a white amorphous powder, possessed the molecular formula C 20 H 20 O 6 , as determined via HR-ESI-MS at m/z 357.1333 [M +H] + (calcd for 357.1338). The NMR data (Tables S7 and S8) of 55 were highly similar to those of bavachinone A ( 63 ) (
), except for the 3 ′′ -hydroxyl group. The protons at C-2 ′′ and C-3 ′′ were at a trans orientation by the small coupling constant ( J ′′ 2,3 ′′ = 4.0 Hz) (
;
). Furthermore, the absolute configuration of 55 was assigned 2 ′′ S ,3 ′′ S based on the configuration of bavachinone A ( 63 ). In summary, the structure of 55 was determined, as shown in Fig. 1 .

Bavachinone H ( 58 ) was obtained as a white amorphous powder, and its molecular formula was determined to be C 21 H 22 O 5 . As elucidated from NMR data (Tables S7 and S8), 58 was derived from bavachinin ( 111 ) (
). The main differences in the NMR signals of these two compounds were the presence of two ortho coupling protons ( J = 11.9 Hz) at δ H 5.00 and δ H 4.51, and a down-field chemical shift value at δ C 74.8 for C- 3 in 58. The NMR analysis indicated that compound 58 was a flavanonol. According to the coupling constant values ( J 2,3 =11.9 Hz) (
), the 3-hydroxyl group and 2-phenyl group were in the trans orientation. Accordingly, the absolute configuration of 58 was determined as 2 R ,3 R and it was named bavachinone G.

Psorachalcone B ( 74 ) was isolated as a yellow amorphous powder, and its molecular formula was determined to be C 21 H 22 O 6 based on HR-ESI-MS at m/z 369.1340 [M – H] – (calcd for 369.1338). In theNMR spectra (Table S9) of 74, a group of signals of trans double bond ( J = 15.2 Hz) at δ H 7.81 and 7.61 was observed, along with a carbonyl signal at δ C 194.3, indicating a chalcone structure (
). The remaining aromatic signals contained two groups of ortho coupling proton, namely δ H 7.62 ( J = 8.6 Hz) and δ H 6.84 assigned to ring B, as well as δ H 8.11 ( J = 8.9 Hz) and δ H 6.50 assigned to ring A. The above analysis showed the presence of an isopentenyl group on C-3’. The isopentenyl group was cyclised to form a dihydrofuran ring with hydroxyl substitutions at C-3 ′′ and C-4 ′′ on the basis of their chemical shift values at δ C 80.8 and δ C 71.9. The HMBC correlation ( Fig. 2 ) from CH 3 at δ H 3.52 to C-3 ′′ at δ C 80.8 showed the linkage position of the methyl group at C-3 ′′ . Then, the relative configurations of C-2 ′′ and C-3 ′′ were assigned trans by the coupling constant values ( J ′′ 2,3 ′′ =2.3 Hz) (
;
). Thus, the structure of 74 was established.

Bavachromone A ( 103 ), a white amorphous powder, possessed the molecular formula C 14 H 14 O 3 , as determined via HR-ESI-MS at m/z 229.0866 [M – H] – (calcd for 229.0865), indicating 8 degrees of unsaturation. A pair of coupling protons ( J 2,3 =6.0 Hz) (Table S11) at δ H 8.00 for H-2 and δ H 6.23 for H-3 were shown in 1 H NMR spectrum, and their cross-peaks with C-4 at δ C 179.8 revealed the presence of pyrone. Upon combining its molecular formula, compound 103 was found to be a chromone with an isopentenyl group, which was linked to C-6 via the key HMBC correlation between H-1 ′ at δ H 3.34 and C-5 at δ C 126.4 ( Fig. 2 ). Thus, the structure of 103 was determined, as shown in Fig. 1 . The molecular formula of bavachromone B ( 104 ) and bavachromone C ( 105 ) was determined to be C 14 H 14 O 4 . Further NMR analysis suggested the same chromone skeletons as that of bavachromone A ( 103 ). Their structures were then established from 1D and 2D NMR spectra. A terminal double bond at C-4 ′ and a hydroxyl replacement at C-2 ′ were observed in compound 104, which was proved by chemical shifts of H-4 ′ at δ H 4.85/4.76 and C-2 ′ at δ C 76.5. The absolute configuration of C-2 ′ was assigned as R on the basis of the negative Cotton effect at 318 nm (
) in the Rh 2 (OCOCF 3 ) 4 -ICD spectrum (Fig. S7). A dihydrofuran ring formed by isopentenyl cyclisation appeared in compound 105 according to carbon chemical shifts ( δ C 93.1 at C-2 ′ , δ C 30.5 at C-3 ′ and δ C 72.5 at C-4 ′ ) and 8 degrees of unsaturation. Similarly, the negative optical value ([ α ]25 D 24) of 105 assigned the chiral centre at C-2 ′ as R (
).

After the separation of the three extracts was completed, the isolation of more than 180 chemical constituents from the fruits of 

P. corylifolia

, allowed us to establish a rich compound library, which is the broadest coverage of the constituent library to date. Next, to identify the active compounds and investigate their SAR, 89 chemical constituents (
Fig. S1
; 
Fig. S3
and Table S16) in the library, covering all 
types
of compounds and consisting of two ones (122 and 123) from 
n
-BuOH extract (

), 80 ones from EtOAc extracts and 7 ones (
114–120
) from cHe extract (Lv et al., 2020; 

), were evaluated for their osteogenic differentiation and mineralisation activities of MC3T3-E1 cells.

Estrogen binding to ER alpha and beta (ERα and ERβ), plays a key role in bone metabolism (

). The expression of ERβ in bone tissue is higher than that of ERα (

; 

). Consequently, in order to explain their SAR in depth, we evaluated the binding affinities of eight compounds and ERβ by SPR technology. The affinity values of the eight compounds and ERβ were shown in 
Fig. 6
. The KD values of most compounds were analyzed using a kinetic model, whereas the KD values of E2, neobavaisoflavone (
42
) and neocorylin (
37
) were obtained using the affinity model. For two coumarins, psoralidin (
13
) (12.4 
μ
M) exhibited a stronger affinity than coumestrol (
11
) (25.0 
μ
M). When it comes to six isoflavones, the KD values of 3 
′
-methoxydaidzein (
46
) and neobavaisoflavone (
42
) were 8.81 and 7.28 
μ
M respectively, indicating stronger affinities than that of daidzein (
44
) (28 
μ
M). In contrast, the affinities of corylifol A (
49
) (54.4 
μ
M), neocorylin (
37
) (96.1 
μ
M) and bakuisoflavone (
47
) (92.8 
μ
M) were weaker than that of daidzein (
44
). Remarkably, compared with E2 (13.9 
μ
M), psoralidin (
13
), neobavaisofalvone (
42
), and 3 
′
-methoxydaidzein (
46
) showed better affinities. The above-mentioned results showed that compounds with an intact isopentenyl replacement possessed a stronger affinity for ERβ than the compounds without isopentenyl substitution or compounds with altered isopentenyl group. Moreover, when a methoxyl group was introduced on C-3 
′
of daidzein, the compound also exhibited a better affinity than daidzein (
44
). Based on the above-mentioned reasons, psoralidin (
13
), neobavaisofalvone (
42
) and 3 
′
-methoxydaidzein (
46
) showed improved results at the cellular level.

Based on the traditional role of 

P. corylifolia

in the treatment of osteoporosis, 89 library constituents were evaluated for their osteogenic differentiation and mineralisation activities of MC3T3-E1 cells, to identify potentially active compounds and investigate their SAR. We found that coumarins, isoflavones, flavonones and meroterpenoids were the basis for the role of 

P. corylifolia

in osteoporosis treatment. Among these constituents, psoralen (
16
), isopsoralen (
17
), coumestrol (
11
), psoralidin (
13
), daidzein (
44
), 3 
′
-methoxydaidzein (
46
), neobavaisoflavone (
42
), corylifol A (
49
), neocorylin (
37
), bavachin (
110
), bavachinin (
111
), bakuchiol (
114
), 12-oxobakuchiol (
118
), corypsoriol A (
121
), genistin (
108
) and astragaline (
109
) exhibited excellent activities. The activities of the representative compounds, psoralidin (
13
) and neobavaisoflavone (
42
), were decreased by the ER antagonist ICI, indicating that these compounds functioned via the ER pathway and were natural PE. Therefore, these compounds could serve as potential drugs or health foods for relieving menopausal symptoms and for the treatment of postmenopausal osteoporosis.

